text: PREFACE
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "There foam'd rebellious Logic, gagg'd and bound."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: This Game requires nine Counters--four of one colour and five of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: another:  say four red and five grey.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Besides the nine Counters, it also requires one Player, AT LEAST.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: I am not aware of any Game that can be played with LESS than this
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: number:  while there are several that require MORE:  take Cricket,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: for instance, which requires twenty-two.  How much easier it is,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: when you want to play a Game, to find ONE Player than twenty-two.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: At the same time, though one Player is enough, a good deal more
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: amusement may be got by two working at it together, and correcting
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: each other's mistakes.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: A second advantage, possessed by this Game, is that, besides being
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: an endless source of amusement (the number of arguments, that may
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: be worked by it, being infinite), it will give the Players a little
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: instruction as well.  But is there any great harm in THAT, so long
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: as you get plenty of amusement?

author: Carroll, Lewis

text: CHAPTER I.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: NEW LAMPS FOR OLD.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Light come, light go."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 1.  Propositions.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Some new Cakes are nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "No new Cakes are nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "All new cakes are nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: There are three 'PROPOSITIONS' for you--the only three kinds we
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are going to use in this Game:  and the first thing to be done is
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to learn how to express them on the Board.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Let us begin with
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Some new Cakes are nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: But before doing so, a remark has to be made--one that is rather
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: important, and by no means easy to understand all in a moment:  so
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: please to read this VERY carefully.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The world contains many THINGS (such as "Buns", "Babies", "Beetles".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Battledores". &c.);  and these Things possess many ATTRIBUTES
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: (such as "baked", "beautiful", "black", "broken", &c.:  in fact,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: whatever can be "attributed to", that is "said to belong to", any
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Thing, is an Attribute).  Whenever we wish to mention a Thing, we
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: use a SUBSTANTIVE:  when we wish to mention an Attribute, we use
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: an ADJECTIVE.  People have asked the question "Can a Thing exist
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: without any Attributes belonging to it?"  It is a very puzzling
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: question, and I'm not going to try to answer it:  let us turn up
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: our noses, and treat it with contemptuous silence, as if it really
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: wasn't worth noticing.  But, if they put it the other way, and ask
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Can an Attribute exist without any Thing for it to belong to?", we
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: may say at once "No:  no more than a Baby could go a railway-journey
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: with no one to take care of it!"  You never saw "beautiful" floating
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: about in the air, or littered about on the floor, without any Thing
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to BE beautiful, now did you?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: And now what am I driving at, in all this long rigmarole?  It is
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: this.  You may put "is" or "are" between names of two THINGS (for
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: example, "some Pigs are fat Animals"), or between the names of two
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: ATTRIBUTES (for example, "pink is light-red"), and in each case it
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: will make good sense.  But, if you put "is" or "are" between the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: name of a THING and the name of an ATTRIBUTE (for example, "some
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Pigs are pink"), you do NOT make good sense (for how can a Thing
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: BE an Attribute?) unless you have an understanding with the person
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to whom you are speaking.  And the simplest understanding would, I
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: think, be this--that the Substantive shall be supposed to be repeated
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: at the end of the sentence, so that the sentence, if written out
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: in full, would be "some Pigs are pink (Pigs)".  And now the word
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "are" makes quite good sense.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Thus, in order to make good sense of the Proposition "some new Cakes
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are nice", we must suppose it to be written out in full, in the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: form "some new Cakes are nice (Cakes)".  Now this contains two
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'TERMS'--"new Cakes" being one of them, and "nice (Cakes)" the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: other.  "New Cakes," being the one we are talking about, is called
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the 'SUBJECT' of the Proposition, and "nice (Cakes)" the 'PREDICATE'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Also this Proposition is said to be a 'PARTICULAR' one, since it
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: does not speak of the WHOLE of its Subject, but only of a PART of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it.  The other two kinds are said to be 'UNIVERSAL', because they
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: speak of the WHOLE of their Subjects--the one denying niceness, and
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the other asserting it, of the WHOLE class of "new Cakes".  Lastly,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: if you would like to have a definition of the word 'PROPOSITION'
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: itself, you may take this:--"a sentence stating that some, or
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: none, or all, of the Things belonging to a certain class, called
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: its 'Subject', are also Things belonging to a certain other class,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: called its 'Predicate'".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: You will find these seven words--PROPOSITION, ATTRIBUTE, TERM,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: SUBJECT, PREDICATE, PARTICULAR, UNIVERSAL--charmingly useful, if
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: any friend should happen to ask if you have ever studied Logic.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Mind you bring all seven words into your answer, and you friend
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: will go away deeply impressed--'a sadder and a wiser man'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Now please to look at the smaller Diagram on the Board, and suppose
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it to be a cupboard, intended for all the Cakes in the world (it
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: would have to be a good large one, of course).  And let us suppose
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: all the new ones to be put into the upper half (marked 'x'), and all
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the rest (that is, the NOT-new ones) into the lower half (marked
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'x'').  Thus the lower half would contain ELDERLY Cakes, AGED
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Cakes, ANTE-DILUVIAN Cakes--if there are any:  I haven't seen many,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: myself--and so on.  Let us also suppose all the nice Cakes to be
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: put into the left-hand half (marked 'y'), and all the rest (that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: is, the not-nice ones) into the right-hand half (marked 'y'').  At
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: present, then, we must understand x to mean "new", x' "not-new",
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: y "nice", and y' "not-nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: And now what kind of Cakes would you expect to find in compartment
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: No. 5?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: It is part of the upper half, you see; so that, if it has any Cakes
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: in it, they must be NEW: and it is part of the left-hand half;
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: so that they must be NICE.  Hence if there are any Cakes in this
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: compartment, they must have the double 'ATTRIBUTE' "new and nice":
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: or, if we use letters, the must be "x y."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Observe that the letters x, y are written on two of the edges of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: this compartment.  This you will find a very convenient rule for
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: knowing what Attributes belong to the Things in any compartment.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Take No. 7, for instance.  If there are any Cakes there, they must
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: be "x' y", that is, they must be "not-new and nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Now let us make another agreement--that a red counter in a
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: compartment shall mean that it is 'OCCUPIED', that is, that there
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are SOME Cakes in it.  (The word 'some,' in Logic, means 'one or
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: more' so that a single Cake in a compartment would be quite enough
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: reason for saying "there are SOME Cakes here").  Also let us agree
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that a grey counter in a compartment shall mean that it is 'EMPTY',
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that is that there are NO Cakes in it.  In the following Diagrams,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: I shall put '1' (meaning 'one or more') where you are to put a RED
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: counter, and '0' (meaning 'none') where you are to put a GREY one.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: As the Subject of our Proposition is to be "new Cakes", we are only
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: concerned, at present, with the UPPER half of the cupboard, where
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: all the Cakes have the attribute x, that is, "new."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Now, fixing our attention on this upper half, suppose we found it
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: marked like this,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that is, with a red counter in No. 5.  What would this tell us,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: with regard to the class of "new Cakes"?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Would it not tell us that there are SOME of them in the x y-compartment?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: That is, that some of them (besides having the Attribute x, which
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: belongs to both compartments) have the Attribute y (that is, "nice").
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: This we might express by saying "some x-Cakes are y-(Cakes)", or,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: putting words instead of letters,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Some new Cakes are nice (Cakes)",
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: or, in a shorter form,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Some new Cakes are nice".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: At last we have found out how to represent the first Proposition
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: of this Section.  If you have not CLEARLY understood all I have
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: said, go no further, but read it over and over again, till you DO
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: understand it.  After that is once mastered, you will find all the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: rest quite easy.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: It will save a little trouble, in doing the other Propositions,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: if we agree to leave out the word "Cakes" altogether.  I find it
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: convenient to call the whole class of Things, for which the cupboard
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: is intended, the 'UNIVERSE.'  Thus we might have begun this business
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: by saying "Let us take a Universe of Cakes."  (Sounds nice, doesn't
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it?)
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Of course any other Things would have done just as well as Cakes.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: We might make Propositions about "a Universe of Lizards", or even
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "a Universe of Hornets".  (Wouldn't THAT be a charming Universe to
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: live in?)
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: So far, then, we have learned that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: means "some x and y," i.e. "some new are nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: I think you will see without further explanation, that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: means "some x are y'," i.e. "some new are not-nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Now let us put a GREY counter into No. 5, and ask ourselves the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: meaning of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: This tells us that the x y-compartment is EMPTY, which we may express
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: by "no x are y", or, "no new Cakes are nice".  This is the second
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: of the three Propositions at the head of this Section.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In the same way,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: would mean "no x are y'," or, "no new Cakes are not-nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: What would you make of this, I wonder?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: I hope you will not have much trouble in making out that this
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: represents a DOUBLE Proposition: namely, "some x are y, AND some
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are y'," i.e. "some new are nice, and some are not-nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The following is a little harder, perhaps:
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: This means "no x are y, AND none are y'," i.e. "no new are nice,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: AND none are not-nice": which leads to the rather curious result
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that "no new exist," i.e. "no Cakes are new."  This is because
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "nice" and "not-nice" make what we call an 'EXHAUSTIVE' division
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: of the class "new Cakes": i.e. between them, they EXHAUST the whole
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: class, so that all the new Cakes, that exist, must be found in one
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: or the other of them.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: And now suppose you had to represent, with counters the contradictory
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to "no Cakes are new", which would be "some Cakes are new", or,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: putting letters for words, "some Cakes are x", how would you do
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: This will puzzle you a little, I expect.  Evidently you must put
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: a red counter SOMEWHERE in the x-half of the cupboard, since you
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: know there are SOME new Cakes.  But you must not put it into the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: LEFT-HAND compartment, since you do not know them to be NICE: nor
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: may you put it into the RIGHT-HAND one, since you do not know them
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to be NOT-NICE.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: What, then, are you to do?  I think the best way out of the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: difficulty is to place the red counter ON THE DIVISION-LINE between
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the xy-compartment and the xy'-compartment.  This I shall represent

text: Two more remarks about Propositions need to be made.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: One is that, in every Proposition beginning with "some" or "all",
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the ACTUAL EXISTENCE of the 'Subject' is asserted.  If, for instance,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: I say "all misers are selfish," I mean that misers ACTUALLY EXIST.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: If I wished to avoid making this assertion, and merely to state
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the LAW that miserliness necessarily involves selfishness, I should
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: say "no misers are unselfish" which does not assert that any misers
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: exist at all, but merely that, if any DID exist, they WOULD be
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: selfish.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The other is that, when a Proposition begins with "some" or "no",
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: and contains more that two Attributes, these Attributes may be
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: re-arranged, and shifted from one Term to the other, "ad libitum."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: For example, "some abc are def" may be re-arranged as "some bf are
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: acde," each being equivalent to "some Things are abcdef".  Again "No
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: wise old men are rash and reckless gamblers" may be re-arranged as
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "No rash old gamblers are wise and reckless," each being equivalent
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to "No men are wise old rash reckless gamblers."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 2.  Syllogisms
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Now suppose we divide our Universe of Things in three ways, with regard
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to three different Attributes.  Out of these three Attributes, we
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: may make up three different couples (for instance, if they were a,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: b, c, we might make up the three couples ab, ac, bc).  Also suppose
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: we have two Propositions given us, containing two of these three
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: couples, and that from them we can prove a third Proposition containing
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the third couple.  (For example, if we divide our Universe for m,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x, and y; and if we have the two Propositions given us, "no m are
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x'" and "all m' are y", containing the two couples mx and my, it
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: might be possible to prove from them a third Proposition, containing
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x and y.)
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In such a case we call the given Propositions 'THE PREMISSES', the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: third one 'THE CONCLUSION' and the whole set 'A SYLLOGISM'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Evidently, ONE of the Attributes must occur in both Premisses; or
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: else one must occur in ONE Premiss, and its CONTRADICTORY in the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: other.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In the first case (when, for example, the Premisses are "some m
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are x" and "no m are y'") the Term, which occurs twice, is called
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'THE MIDDLE TERM', because it serves as a sort of link between the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: other two Terms.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In the second case (when, for example, the Premisses are "no
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: m are x'" and "all m' are y") the two Terms, which contain these
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: contradictory Attributes, may be called 'THE MIDDLE TERMS'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Thus, in the first case, the class of "m-Things" is the Middle
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Term; and, in the second case, the two classes of "m-Things" and
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "m'-Things" are the Middle Terms.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The Attribute, which occurs in the Middle Term or Terms, disappears
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: in the Conclusion, and is said to be "eliminated", which literally
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: means "turned out of doors".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Now let us try to draw a Conclusion from the two Premisses--
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Some new Cakes are unwholesome;
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: No nice Cakes are unwholesome."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In order to express them with counters, we need to divide Cakes in
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: THREE different ways, with regard to newness, to niceness, and to
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: wholesomeness.  For this we must use the larger Diagram, making x
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: mean "new", y "nice", and m "wholesome".  (Everything INSIDE the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: central Square is supposed to have the attribute m, and everything
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: OUTSIDE it the attribute m', i.e. "not-m".)

author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Let us see what we can make of the two Premisses--

author: Carroll, Lewis

author: Carroll, Lewis

author: Carroll, Lewis

author: Carroll, Lewis

title: The Game of Logic

author: Carroll, Lewis

author: Carroll, Lewis

text: of Conclusions.

author: Carroll, Lewis

title: The Game of Logic

title: The Game of Logic

title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Let me mention, in conclusion, that you may perhaps meet with
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: logical treatises in which it is not assumed that any Thing EXISTS
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: at all, by "some x are y" is understood to mean "the Attributes x,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: y are COMPATIBLE, so that a Thing can have both at once", and "no
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x are y" to mean "the Attributes x, y are INCOMPATIBLE, so that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: nothing can have both at once".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In such treatises, Propositions have quite different meanings
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: from what they have in our 'Game of Logic', and it will be well to
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: understand exactly what the difference is.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: First take "some x are y".  Here WE understand "are" to mean "are,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: as an actual FACT"--which of course implies that some x-Things EXIST.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: But THEY (the writers of these other treatises) only understand
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "are" to mean "CAN be", which does not at all imply that any EXIST.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: So they mean LESS than we do: our meaning includes theirs (for of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: course "some x ARE y" includes "some x CAN BE y"), but theirs does
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: NOT include ours.  For example, "some Welsh hippopotami are heavy"
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: would be TRUE, according to these writers (since the Attributes
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "Welsh" and "heavy" are quite COMPATIBLE in a hippopotamus), but
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it would be FALSE in our Game (since there are no Welsh hippopotami
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to BE heavy).
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Secondly, take "no x are y".  Here WE only understand "are" to
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: mean "are, as an actual FACT"--which does not at all imply that no
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x CAN be y.  But THEY understand the Proposition to mean, not only
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that none ARE y, but that none CAN POSSIBLY be y.  So they mean
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: more than we do: their meaning includes ours (for of course "no x
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: CAN be y" includes "no x ARE y"), but ours does NOT include theirs.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: For example, "no Policemen are eight feet high" would be TRUE
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: in our Game (since, as an actual fact, no such splendid specimens
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are ever found), but it would be FALSE, according to these writers
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: (since the Attributes "belonging to the Police Force" and "eight
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: feet high" are quite COMPATIBLE:  there is nothing to PREVENT a
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Policeman from growing to that height, if sufficiently rubbed with
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Rowland's Macassar Oil--which said to make HAIR grow, when rubbed
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: on hair, and so of course will make a POLICEMAN grow, when rubbed
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: on a Policeman).
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Thirdly, take "all x are y", which consists of the two partial
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Propositions "some x are y" and "no x are y'".  Here, of course,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the treatises mean LESS than we do in the FIRST part, and more than
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: we do in the SECOND.  But the two operations don't balance each
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: other--any more than you can console a man, for having knocked down
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: one of his chimneys, by giving him an extra door-step.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: If you meet with Syllogisms of this kind, you may work them, quite
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: easily, by the system I have given you: you have only to make
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'are' mean 'are CAPABLE of being', and all will go smoothly.  For
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "some x are y" will become "some x are capable of being y", that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: is, "the Attributes x, y are COMPATIBLE".  And "no x are y" will
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: become "no x are capable of being y", that is, "the Attributes
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x, y are INCOMPATIBLE".  And, of course, "all x are y" will become
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "some x are capable of being y, and none are capable of being y'",
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that is, "the Attributes x, y are COMPATIBLE, and the Attributes
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: x, y' are INCOMPATIBLE."  In using the Diagrams for this system,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: you must understand a red counter to mean "there may POSSIBLY be
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: something in this compartment," and a grey one to mean "there cannot
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: POSSIBLY be anything in this compartment."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 3. Fallacies.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: And so you think, do you, that the chief use of Logic, in real life,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: is to deduce Conclusions from workable Premisses, and to satisfy
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: yourself that the Conclusions, deduced by other people, are correct?
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: I only wish it were!  Society would be much less liable to panics
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: and other delusions, and POLITICAL life, especially, would be a
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: totally different thing, if even a majority of the arguments, that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: scattered broadcast over the world, were correct!  But it is all
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the other way, I fear.  For ONE workable Pair of Premisses (I mean
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: a Pair that lead to a logical Conclusion) that you meet with in
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: reading your newspaper or magazine, you will probably find FIVE
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that lead to no Conclusion at all: and, even when the Premisses
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: ARE workable, for ONE instance, where the writer draws a correct
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Conclusion, there are probably TEN where he draws an incorrect one.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In the first case, you may say "the PREMISSES are fallacious": in
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the second, "the CONCLUSION is fallacious."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The chief use you will find, in such Logical skill as this Game
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: may teach you, will be in detecting 'FALLACIES' of these two kinds.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The first kind of Fallacy--'Fallacious Premisses'--you will detect
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: when, after marking them on the larger Diagram, you try to transfer
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the marks to the smaller.  You will take its four compartments, one
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: by one, and ask, for each in turn, "What mark can I place HERE?";
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: and in EVERY one the answer will be "No information!", showing that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: there is NO CONCLUSION AT ALL.  For instance,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "All soldiers are brave;
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Some Englishmen are brave.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: &there4 Some Englishmen are soldiers."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: looks uncommonly LIKE a Syllogism, and might easily take in a
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: less experienced Logician.  But YOU are not to be caught by such
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: a trick!  You would simply set out the Premisses, and would then
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: calmly remark "Fallacious PREMISSES!": you wouldn't condescend to
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: ask what CONCLUSION the writer professed to draw--knowing that,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: WHATEVER it is, it MUST be wrong.  You would be just as safe as
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that wise mother was, who said "Mary, just go up to the nursery,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: and see what Baby's doing, AND TELL HIM NOT TO DO IT!"
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: The other kind of Fallacy--'Fallacious Conclusion'--you will not
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: detect till you have marked BOTH Diagrams, and have read off the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: correct Conclusion, and have compared it with the Conclusion which
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the writer has drawn.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: But mind, you mustn't say "FALLACIOUS Conclusion," simply because
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it is not IDENTICAL with the correct one: it may be a PART of the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: correct Conclusion, and so be quite correct, AS FAR AS IT GOES.  In
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: this case you would merely remark, with a pitying smile, "DEFECTIVE
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Conclusion!" Suppose, of example, you were to meet with this
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Syllogism:--
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "All unselfish people are generous;
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: No misers are generous.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: &there4 No misers are unselfish."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: No y are m."

author: Carroll, Lewis

title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: by the writer, is "No y are x'," (which is the same as "No x' are
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: y," and so is PART of "All x' are y'.")  Here you would simply say
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "DEFECTIVE Conclusion!" The same thing would happen, if you were
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: in a confectioner's shop, and if a little boy were to come in, put

title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "But why is this?" you will say.  "Do you mean to tell us that all
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: these Logicians are wrong?"  Far from it, dear Reader!  From THEIR
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: point of view, they are perfectly right.  But they do not include,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: in their system, anything like ALL the possible forms of Syllogisms.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: They have a sort of nervous dread of Attributes beginning with a
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: negative particle.  For example, such Propositions as "All not-x
title: The Game of Logic

text: are y," "No x are not-y," are quite outside their system.  And
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: thus, having (from sheer nervousness) excluded a quantity of very
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: useful forms, they have made rules which, though quite applicable
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to the few forms which they allow of, are no use at all when you
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: consider all possible forms.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Let us not quarrel with them, dear Reader!  There is room enough in
title: The Game of Logic

text: the world for both of us.  Let us quietly take our broader system:
title: The Game of Logic

title: The Game of Logic

text: yours, upon which it is so dangerous to Rush, as your Fate.  You
title: The Game of Logic

title: The Game of Logic

title: The Game of Logic

text: "I answered him, as I thought good,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'As many as red-herrings grow in the wood'."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 1.  Elementary.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 1.  Whatever can be "attributed to", that is "said to belong to",
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: a Thing, is called an 'Attribute'.  For example, "baked", which
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: can (frequently) be attributed to "Buns", and "beautiful", which
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: can (seldom) be attributed to "Babies".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 2.  When they are the Names of two Things (for example, "these
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Pigs are fat Animals"), or of two Attributes (for example, "pink
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: is light red").
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 3.  When one is the Name of a Thing, and the other the Name of an
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Attribute (for example, "these Pigs are pink"), since a Thing cannot
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: actually BE an Attribute.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 4.  That the Substantive shall be supposed to be repeated at the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: end of the sentence (for example, "these Pigs are pink (Pigs)").
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 5.  A 'Proposition' is a sentence stating that some, or none, or all,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: of the Things belonging to a certain class, called the 'Subject',
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are also Things belonging to a certain other class, called the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'Predicate'.  For example, "some new Cakes are not nice", that is
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: (written in full) "some new Cakes are not nice Cakes"; where the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: class "new Cakes" is the Subject, and the class "not-nice Cakes"
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: is the Predicate.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 6.  A Proposition, stating that SOME of the Things belonging to
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: its Subject are so-and-so, is called 'Particular'.  For example,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "some new Cakes are nice", "some new Cakes are not nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: A Proposition, stating that NONE of the Things belonging to its
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Subject, or that ALL of them, are so-and-so, is called 'Universal'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: For example, "no new Cakes are nice", "all new Cakes are not nice".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 7.  The Things in each compartment possess TWO Attributes, whose
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: symbols will be found written on two of the EDGES of that compartment.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 8.  "One or more."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 9.  As a name of the class of Things to which the whole Diagram is
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: assigned.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 10.  A Proposition containing two statements.  For example, "some
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: new Cakes are nice and some are not-nice."
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 11.  When the whole class, thus divided, is "exhausted" among the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: sets into which it is divided, there being no member of it which
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: does not belong to some one of them.  For example, the class "new
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Cakes" is "exhaustively" divided into "nice" and "not-nice" since
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: EVERY new Cake must be one or the other.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 12.  When a man cannot make up his mind which of two parties he
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: will join, he is said to be "sitting on the fence"--not being able
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: to decide on which side he will jump down.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 13.  "Some x are y" and "no x are y'".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 14.  A Proposition, whose Subject is a single Thing, is called
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'Individual'.  For example, "I am happy", "John is not at home".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: These are Universal Propositions, being the same as "all the I's
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: that exist are happy", "ALL the Johns, that I am now considering,
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: are not at home".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 15.  Propositions beginning with "some" or "all".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 16.  When they begin with "some" or "no".  For example, "some
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: abc are def" may be re-arranged as "some bf are acde", each being
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: equivalent to "some abcdef exist".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 17.  Some tigers are fierce, No tigers are not-fierce.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 18.  Some hard-boiled eggs are unwholesome, No hard-boiled
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: eggs are wholesome.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 19.  Some I's are happy, No I's are unhappy.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 20.  Some Johns are not at home, No Johns are at home.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 21.  The Things, in each compartment of the larger Diagram, possess
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: THREE Attributes, whose symbols will be found written at three of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the CORNERS of the compartment (except in the case of m', which is
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: not actually inserted in the Diagram, but is SUPPOSED to stand at
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: each of its four outer corners).
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 22.  If the Universe of Things be divided with regard to three
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: different Attributes; and if two Propositions be given, containing
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: two different couples of these Attributes; and if from these we
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: can prove a third Proposition, containing the two Attributes that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: have not yet occurred together; the given Propositions are called
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'the Premisses', the third one 'the Conclusion', and the whole set
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'a Syllogism'.  For example, the Premisses might be "no m are x'"
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: and "all m' are y"; and it might be possible to prove from them
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: a Conclusion containing x and y.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 23.  If an Attribute occurs in both Premisses, the Term containing
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: it is called 'the Middle Term'.  For example, if the Premisses are
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: "some m are x" and "no m are y'", the class of "m-Things" is 'the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Middle Term.'
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: If an Attribute occurs in one Premiss, and its contradictory in the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: other, the Terms containing them may be called 'the Middle Terms'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: For example, if the Premisses are "no m are x'" and "all m' are
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: y", the two classes of "m-Things" and "m'-Things" may be called
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 'the Middle Terms'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 24.  Because they can be marked with CERTAINTY: whereas AFFIRMATIVE
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Propositions (that is, those that begin with "some" or "all")
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: sometimes require us to place a red counter 'sitting on a fence'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 25.  Because the only question we are concerned with is whether the
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Conclusion FOLLOWS LOGICALLY from the Premisses, so that, if THEY
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: were true, IT also would be true.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 26.  By understanding a red counter to mean "this compartment CAN
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: be occupied", and a grey one to mean "this compartment CANNOT be
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: occupied" or "this compartment MUST be empty".
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 27.  'Fallacious Premisses' and 'Fallacious Conclusion'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 28.  By finding, when we try to transfer marks from the larger
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: Diagram to the smaller, that there is 'no information' for any of
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: its four compartments.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 29.  By finding the correct Conclusion, and then observing that
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: the Conclusion, offered to us, is neither identical with it nor a
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: part of it.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: 30.  When the offered Conclusion is PART of the correct Conclusion.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis

text: In this case, we may call it a 'Defective Conclusion'.
title: The Game of Logic
author: Carroll, Lewis
